  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    A 3x5-inch index card is&amp;nbsp;the typical way to record a user story.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The front of the card is used to capture the user story sentence, which typically follows the&amp;nbsp;notation shown in&#xD;
    Figure 1.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 1. Typical front of a user story card&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Front of user story card&quot; src=&quot;./resources/card_front_with_text.jpg&quot; />&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The back of the card is used to capture relevant details that come up during conversations with stakeholders, such as&#xD;
    information or data needed, nonfunctional requirements (such as performance or scalability) and&amp;nbsp;other conditions&#xD;
    of satisfaction for the user story. The back of the card can be organized&amp;nbsp;as&amp;nbsp;Figure 2 shows.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;strong>Figure 2. Typical back of a user story card&lt;/strong>&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p align=&quot;left&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Back of user story card&quot; src=&quot;./resources/card_back_with_text.jpg&quot; />&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
